{"id":"1507.08587","submitter":"Karol Bartkiewicz","authors":"Adam Miranowicz, Karol Bartkiewicz, Neill Lambert, Yueh-Nan Chen,\n  Franco Nori","title":"Increasing relative nonclassicality quantified by standard entanglement\n  potentials by dissipation and unbalanced beam splitting","comments":"13 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 92, 062314 (2015)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.92.062314","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  If a single-mode nonclassical light is combined with the vacuum on a beam\nsplitter, then the output state is entangled. As proposed in [Phys. Rev. Lett.\n94, 173602 (2005)], by measuring the output-state entanglement for a balanced\nlossless beam splitter, one can quantify the input-state nonclassicality. These\nmeasures of nonclassicality (referred to as entanglement potentials) can be\nbased, in principle, on various entanglement measures, leading to the\nnegativity (NP) and concurrence (CP) potentials, and the potential for the\nrelative entropy of entanglement (REEP). We search for the maximal\nnonclassicality, which can be achieved by comparing two entanglement measures\nfor arbitrary two-qubit states and those which can be generated from a\nphoton-number qubit via a balanced lossless beam-splitter, where the qubit\nbasis states are the vacuum and single-photon states. Surprisingly, we find\nthat the maximal nonclassicality, measured by the REEP for a given value of the\nNP, can be increased (if NP<0.527) by using either a tunable beam splitter or\nby amplitude damping of the output state of the balanced beam splitter. We also\nshow that the maximal nonclassicality, measured by the NP for a given value of\nthe REEP, can be increased by dephasing. The entanglement itself is not\nincreased by these local losses, but the possible ratios of different measures\nare affected. Moreover, we show that partially-mixed states can be more\nnonclassical than both pure states and completely-mixed states, by comparing\nthe NP for a given value of the REEP. This implies that not all entanglement\nmeasures can be used as entanglement potentials. Alternatively, a single\nbalanced lossless beam splitter is not always transferring the whole\nnonclassicality of its input state into the entanglement of its output modes.\nApplying a lossy beam splitter can solve this problem at least for the cases\nanalyzed in this paper.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 30 Jul 2015 17:12:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 10 Dec 2015 12:00:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-12-11"}
